explanation:
- OS_ShellOutputToFile_Impl: The implementation called by the target function is the most likely place string.h functions (memcpy/strcpy/strlen/...) would be used to write Cmd into the file. Its source is required to verify any buffer accesses and length checks.
- OS_CHECK_POINTER: Macro used at the start of the target function. It may perform the null check or call other helpers (or even call OS_printf/return error codes). Need its definition to confirm it does not perform any unsafe string operations or alter control flow relevant to buffer-safety.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Acquires the token passed to the Impl. Its behavior determines whether the token passed to Impl is valid and whether any side-effects could affect string handling (e.g. initialization of structures, error returns). The implementation is needed to reason about the success/failure path and any interactions with Cmd or memory ownership.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Releases the token after Impl returns. Needed to ensure no post-call side-effects affect safety analysis and to inspect whether release semantics could relate to lifetime of buffers referenced by the token/Impl.
- OS_object_token_t: Type of the token passed to Impl. The token layout may include pointers or buffer descriptors; knowing its structure is necessary to determine whether Impl will copy or reference internal buffers and whether string routines might access out-of-bounds memory.
- osal_id_t: Type of the file descriptor parameter. Its representation may affect which object is selected (stream vs other), and may influence Impl behavior. Include to fully understand calling conventions and possible value ranges.
- OS_SUCCESS: The success return code checked before calling Impl. Required to reason about control flow (whether Impl is called) and which code paths to analyze for string usage.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT and OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_STREAM: Constants passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById. They determine which object and mode are retrieved; this can change token contents/behavior and therefore influence whether Impl performs string operations on particular object types.
- OS_INVALID_POINTER: Likely error code used by OS_CHECK_POINTER; include to understand early-return semantics and whether the function can exit before any string handling occurs.
- OS_printf: Included because OS_CHECK_POINTER or error paths may call it (or other macros may use it). If used, its implementation or wrappers could themselves use string routines; at minimum include to inspect side-effects or formatting behavior.
- int32: The integer typedef used for return type; include the typedef to ensure correct interpretation of return values and error codes.

These symbols provide the minimal context (macro definitions, the Impl body, token/type definitions and the object-get/release semantics) needed to determine whether any string.h functions are invoked on Cmd (or other buffers) and whether those invocations can access memory beyond object bounds.
